The theme is so Shakespearean. It's distinctively Elizabethan, and the more
I read it the more I like it. (Read it quickly and out loud -- it flows
beautifully.) It is very densely packed, and full of complex imagery. The
author shows a willingness to break rules. In this case it's addressed to a
dominating and rather fear-inspiring woman -- although
the author is not afraid to say what he thinks about her in the poem. If it
is Oxford's (as I am now fairly sure) the only likely candidate would be
Elizabeth, and that would have been the reason for excluding it from the
Canon.

