When I was 16 years old, I was passionately devoted to the work of Walt
Whitman.
Even a 16-year-old, of course, with any discernment, discerns that Whitman's
poetry is uneven; some of it is just downright godawful. But I especially
loved &quot;When lilacs...&quot;. I would often seek solitude and read it aloud to
myself,
over and over and over again.

When I grew to man's estate, I began to find all of Whitman utterly unreadable,
and I simply cannot read him to this day. I sometimes wonder whether I would
find
his poetry appealing now had I not loved it then.

I don't have it in front of me, so I'm paraphrasing from memory, but in his
&quot;Devil's Dictionary&quot;, Ambrose Bierce defined the word &quot;incompossibles&quot; as,
roughly,
things that cannot possibly coexist, and gave as an example Walt Whitman's
poetry and God's mercy to man--a sentiment that I have come to appreciate.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;A good idea. I still find it odd that no one mentioned Shakespeare as a
&gt;first choice.

"/>

I think that Shakespeare's sonnets, taken as a whole, constitute the finest
lyric poetry in English. But they are not a unitary work, and it would be
difficult indeed to pick one of them and say that this single lyric is the
finest in the language (as if one could meaningfully say such a thing about
any single lyric).

But allow me to add to the growing list of people's favorites a few of my own.

&quot;On Wenlock Edge&quot; and &quot;Is My Team Plowing&quot;, by A.E. Housman. I suppose Housman
has suffered something of a critical eclipse, but his best is very good indeed.
These are my favorites.

&quot;Channel Firing&quot; by Thomas Hardy. Hardy is the only writer in English I can
think of who was both a great novelist and a great poet, and this is fittingly
his most famous poem. The last lines are, to me, among the most beautifully
modulated
words in English:

Again the guns disturbed the hour,
Roaring their readiness to avenge,
As far inland as Stourton Tower,
And Camelot, and starlit Stonehenge.

&quot;September 1, 1939&quot; by W.H. Auden. Read it and weep. A model of a poet's
&quot;engagement&quot; in the world. &quot;All I have is a voice / to undo the folded lie....&quot;

&quot;Felix Randall&quot; by Gerard Manley Hopkins. Others have mentioned other poems
by Hopkins; this is a particular favorite of mine. Orwell wrote a lovely piece
about it.

&quot;The Rime of the Ancient Mariner&quot; by Coleridge. I'm kind of surprised no one
else has proposed this. An astonishing piece of work.

&quot;The City of Dreadful Night&quot; by James Thomson. This is the 19th-century poet
of that name, not the 18th-century poet of &quot;The Seasons&quot; and &quot;The Castle of
Indolence&quot;. Not very well known nowadays, but &quot;The City of Dreadful Night&quot;,
while
certainly a deeply flawed work, is one of the most powerful things I've ever
read.
Unlike the other poems I've proposed, this one is perhaps unknown to many who
read
the present lines; here is an online copy:

&quot;Dover Beach&quot; by Matthew Arnold. Others have proposed it, and I second that
emotion.
Many years ago, when I was first exposed to computers (this was before PCs), I
was
learning the text editor of the system I worked on, and used &quot;Dover Beach&quot; as
practice
text. So I typed in the last stanza, only to find the next day that someone on
this
multi-user system had altered it. It read as follows:

Ah, love, let us be true
To one another! for the world, which seems
To lie before us like a land of dreams,
So various, so beautiful, so new,
Hath really neither joy, nor love, nor light,
Nor certitude, nor peace, nor help for pain;
And we are here as on a darkling plain
Swept with confused alarms of struggle and flight,
Where ignorant armies clash by night,
And where every little breeze
Seems to whisper Louise
And the skies are not cloudy all day.

This of course leads one to remember the immortal Spike Milligan's immortal
parody
of the immortal John Masefield's immortal &quot;Sea Fever&quot;:

I must go down to the sea again,
to the lonely sea and the sky,
I left my vest and socks there:
I wonder if they're dry?

But perhaps I digress. Forgive the long excursus from a habitual lurker.

H.

.

