"/>

Haven't been around for a while, but this thread looked interesting, so I went
back to the intro post. First off, I'd want a definition of &quot;greatest poem.&quot;
One major problem for me is the difference between a highly effective poem that
is &quot;only&quot; the best of its kind, and a less effective, even failed, poem that is
the first of a kind with great potential. I think, for instance, of Pound's
CANTOS; although some of them are very effective, the poem as a whole is, I
think, a failure--but it may still be the greatest poem in English because of
all its done for poetry. (No, I don't think it is.)

Jim is right in the huge problem is judging a long poem against a short one, but
your nomination implies you mean short lyrics. (And I think you mean &quot;most
effective&quot; as opposed necessarily to &quot;greatest.&quot;) Even so, it's hard to compare
a mid-length lyric like &quot;Tintern Abbey&quot; with a shorter one like one of
Shakespeare's sonnets, or either with &quot;lighght.&quot;

A third large problem usually ignored is that no one is familiar enough with the
full range of poetry in English to nominate anything. Of course, some of us
assume we're being asked for the greatest poem in English we know of rather than
simply the greatest poem in English, but I fear most people take it for granted
that they know all the candidates.

I think it's a good question (granted my assumptions about size and
effectiveness), anyway--and probably answerable. That is, I do believe there is
one best short lyric in English. On the other hand, I doubt that there is one
that's more than half-a-molecule better than whatever's second. I'd nominate
ten or twenty by Yeats, ten or twenty by Stevens, most of Keats's odes, several
by Cummings and Roethke and Larkin and Hardy, a few by Frost, some by Pound
(particularly if one is allowed to count some of his Cantos a stand-alone
poems), one or two by WC Williams, possibly as many as a hundred by people no
one at HLAS has ever heard of (unless I've mentioned them here), nothing by
Whitman or Shakespeare or TS Eliot or Blake or Dickinson of Browning. Some by
Wordsworth and Shelley and Swinburne. One, each, by twenty or thirty poets like
Marvell. I'm sure I've forgotten a bunch, and been unfair to others.

Note: a poet can succeed at the highest level without every writing a single
super poem--for instance, take the accomplishment of Ted Hughes's &quot;Crow.&quot; I
don't think any individual poem in that collection is in the running for best
poem in English, but the group as a whole is major, in my opinion.

--Bob G.

