...
Two that occur to me:

Loveliest of trees, the cherry now
Is hung with bloom along the bough
And stands about the woodland wide
Wearing white for Easter-tide.

(Liturgically correct, I undertand - Housman described himself as a
high-church atheist. The next stanza is less memorable: I have
forgotten it, except as an exercise in versified simple arithmetic,
the answer being that he can expect to live another fifty years. But
the last one rises again, almost to the level of the first.)

And since, to look at things in bloom
Fifty springs is little room,
About the woodland I will go
To see the cherry, hung with snow.

Then there is a longer one that begins very well:

High the vanes of Shrewsbury gleam
Islanded in Severn's stream
And bridges from the steepled crest
Cross the water, east and west.

The flag of morn, in conqueror's state,
Enters at the English gate;
The vanquished eve, as night prevails,
Bleeds upon the road to Wales.

(The rest is not equal to this. Looking at the plan of Shrewsbury in
Lord Burghley's atlas, I realised this poem was most likely based on
that and not on an actual view of the city.)

Having all my books under dust-sheets at the moment, I am limited to
poets who are easy to remember. Which may make it topical to remark
that Shakespeare's Sonnets are definitely hard to memorise. Every word
is vital and few are obvious.
--
Robert Stonehouse
