tinkles&quot; - better, I think than &quot;It just jingles&quot;) is devoted to the
question of why the poet &quot;appealed so deeply to the people [he means
boys, having in the preceding paragraph doubted that girls found much
in his work] who were young in 1920&quot;, arguing that the reason was a
combination of nostalgia for the countryside, attention to matters
that interest adolescent males and &quot;his blasphemous, antinomian,
'cynical' strain&quot;. He concludes the section with what I regard as one
of his poorer judgements: &quot;But at bottom it is always a writer's
tendency, his 'purpose', his 'message', that makes him liked or
disliked. The proof of this is the extreme difficulty of seeing any
literary merit in a book that seriously damages your deepest beliefs.&quot;
Those sentences are reminders of why and how Orwell was a man of the
Left rather than the Right.

