What he said has some relation to politics, but only because political
beliefs are part of what makes up someone's vision of how the world is or
ought to be. Religion, for example, is at least as powerful a component of
that vision as politics. I also think you're mistaking what Orwell said for
a personal credo, whereas it was in fact merely an observation about a very
human tendency to withold praise from otherwise well-written books, if those
books promote beliefs we do not ourselves share. It's an observation that
holds good in any period of history, and involves beliefs that might not
necessarily be political. Witness the tendency of Stratfordians to dismiss
Oxfordian books as &quot;poorly written&quot;, and vice versa.

There were certainly some on the Left in the 'thirties who took the view
that only Leftist books could be accorded literary merit, but Orwell was not
one of them. He was merely doing what it was his habit to do, which was to
bring to our attention some disreputable aspect of human behaviour, and
promptly include himself amongst the guilty ones.

