P. 250 suggests Performance:: Revealing the Orpheus within

P. 251-2 Tofts suggests, &quot;First, consider the passions of the poem.
Note the dominant affection and determine how the main parts of the
text relate to this central passion. Then study individual sentences
to discover the specific affections embodied in them.

At the same time, observe the figurative language with which sentences
have been decorated and decide which words require emphasis. Do not
overlook the punctuation, for it is the vehicle through which the
structure of the discourse is articulated, and the observance of it
enables listeners to comprehend the thoughts and emotions of the texts
easily. At this point the study of the structure of the text should be
complete.&quot;

