If you're referring to _Yevgenii Onegin_, there are popular verse
translations by Babette Deutsch, Walter Arndt, Charles Johnston, and
James Falen, and even Douglas Hofstadter, among others. Nabokov
ridiculed the existing verse translations into English, and Nabokov's
own famously idiosyncratic translation and brilliant commentary has much
to offer; however, the fidelity to nuance upon which Nabokov insisted
precluded a translation retaining the verse and meter of the original,
and despite its many felicities and the care Nabokov lavished upon it,
Nabokov's translation does not really permit a reader with no Russian to
glimpse Pushkin's sprightly and sparkling virtuosity.

I would enthusiastically recommend Jim Falen's superb translation,
which in my opinion is by far the best of the English verse translations
available. Nabokov's commentary is fascinating, and reading it
concurrently is very rewarding; however, this is a work notorious for
frustrating translators and hence is best read in Russian.

